Congratulations to Sarah Cao!

The Connecticut Scholars Committee of the Connecticut Association of

Schools (CAS) has selected Sarah as one of the 2020 Connecticut Scholars. Sarah was selected from an entry pool of the top juniors in Connecticut’s high schools.

The purpose of the Connecticut Scholars Program is to recognize academically talented grade Eleven high school students in schools throughout the state. Members of the Connecticut Scholars Committee and professional educators from throughout Connecticut judged this year’s completed nominations and assigned a composite score to each nominee based on PSAT scores and the essay.



Congratulations to Sarah for representing E.O. Smith as a 2020 Connecticut Scholar.

post_text: The E.O. Smith French program has been awarded the distinction of "Exemplary Program with Honors" by the American Association of Teachers of French. Criteria for this distinction include: evidence of strong project-based curricula with standards-based assessments; high student enrollment; AP and ECE programs; travel, honor society and service learning opportunities. Former students, parents of current students, colleagues and administrators also wrote letters of support for the program. Félicitations E.O. Smith!

The E.O. Smith Chamber Singers have been selected as a performing/showcase ensemble at the 2020 ACDA Division Conference
(The American Choral Directors Association), in Rochester, New York, March 5, 2020.

The Eastern Division of ACDA is comprised of 12 states.
13 choirs were chosen (through a blind audition process) as ensembles who exemplify excellence in the choral arts
and we are 1 of 3 high school choirs to receive this incredible honor.

Here is the official press release, via the ACDA East website:
https://acdaeast.org/division-conferences/rochester-2020/rochester-acceptedchoirs/?fbclid=IwAR08fs8hstQBdFabcmEH8O9buBtIc86GLv8gNT6vycBWQHi2bP_DlezgXHI

The Chamber Singers are an extraordinary group of musicians and this kind of National-level honor is unique and rare.
Over the past 20 years, there have only been 6 other Connecticut Choirs represented at ACDA Division.

National Merit Finalists will compete for one of 2,500 National Merit $2,500 scholarships. The awards will be announced this spring. This is the 65th year of the prestigious program, which honors academically talented high school seniors who are selected on the basis of their skills, accomplishments, and potential success in rigorous college studies.

Congratulations, Ethan!

Looking In theater company, recipient of the 2017 Katherine Hepburn Award given by the CT Commission on Human Rights, performed at two interdisciplinary assemblies and conducted an after school workshop with the E.O. Smith Drama Club on Tuesday, November 19. These performances/workshops attended by over 300 students were funded by a generous grant from the University of Connecticut's ECE program.

In March, Ms. Desjarlais' ECE Human Rights and Ms. Abercrombie's Drama classes will continue to work with Jonathan Gillman's Looking In theater company. The two classes will create a range of original scenes about important social issues and hope to present their work at a spring showcase. If you're interested in joining Drama class or taking ECE Human Rights, sign up in Guidance!

The E.O. Smith Drama Club will host open auditions for roles in The Dream Rehearsed,

The Imagined First Rehearsal of Shakespeare's A Midsummer Night's Dream, on Wednesday 11/20 and Thursday 11/21 after school from 2:30-5:30 p.m. in the E.O. Smith auditorium.



Copies of the play are available in the English office and an audition sign-up sheet will be outside the English office doorway. The play will be staged under the direction of Carol Macy. Many parts are available for a range of student actors!



All students interested in light, sound, set design, costuming, stage management are encouraged to attend either audition date. to audition for this production to be performed on Fri., February 28, Sat., Feb. 29, and Sun., March 1. We also plan to stage the show at the Connecticut Drama Association Festival (March 13-14).

post_text: Registration for the October 16th PSAT NMSQT will begin Monday September 16th through Wednesday, October 9th. This PSAT NMSQT is part of the SAT suite of assessment series. Grade 11 students taking the PSAT NMSQT are eligible in qualifying for the National Merit Scholarship Program. Please note all grade 10 students will be given the PSAT free of charge in March of 2020. The exam is open to both grade 9 and 10 students; however, it is recommended that students have completed geometry or are concurrently enrolled. Sign-up will take place in the school counseling office. The cost is $17. Please contact your counselor if you have any questions.

He talked about Social Studies teacher Tim Bowen always doing an outstanding job in preparing and leading students in the discussion. Not shying away from the tough questions, the students and He had a chance to discuss a range of topics in detail, including volume one of the Mueller report which included findings of the investigation into Russian interference in the 2016 presidential election, and volume two which investigated any potential obstruction of justice by the President. He also discussed a range of issues facing the students themselves, such as college affordability and the post 9/11 G.I. bill benefits, of which one of the students is a benefactor.

post_text: Please plan on joining us on May 18th at 6:00 PM for this night of fun and support for the Edwin O. Smith Foundation. Tickets are $25 per person and include all food and live entertainment; drinks are not included in the admission price. Tickets can be purchased at the door the night of the event or at www.eosmithfoundation.org. There will be a DJ, fresh food served buffet style, a silent auction, and so much more. The event is being held once again at The Sports Bar located at 157 Boston Post Road, North Windham, CT. The silent auction includes many sought after items which are donated by alumni, local businesses and friends of E. O. Smith. Proceeds from the night go directly to the Foundation which funds the grants and scholarships they award every year. Sponsorship and donation opportunities are still available for local businesses who would like to help the Foundation. Please go to www.eosmithfoundation.org for information and to buy tickets!

post_text:
UCONN Today- features the STAAR Program

https://today.uconn.edu/2019/04/s-t-r-unique-class-basement-uconns-sprague-hall/#

In today's UCONN Today, the STAAR Program is featured.
S.T.A.A.R. is a transitional program for students ages 18 to 21 that is designed to help young adults living with developmental disabilities continue their learning, develop vocational and independent living skills, and enhance their social relationships in a college-based setting.
The program began with one student in 2005 and now includes an average of 20 students each year, all of whom have previously completed four years of high school either at E.O. Smith High School in Storrs or at a high school from another area town. S.T.A.A.R.’s integration with the University’s campus – and with UConn students – is part of the program’s appeal for prospective students and their families.

CONNECTICUT HIGH SCHOOL OUTSTANDING ARTS AWARDS RECIPIENTS HONORED AT CAS BANQUET

Cooper Clark and Josie Redding were two of 286 top Connecticut seniors who excel in the arts that were honored at the Connecticut Association of Schools (CAS) High School Outstanding Arts Awards Banquet held on April 2nd at the Aqua Turf in Southington. The CAS Outstanding Arts Awards Banquet annually recognizes two seniors in each member high school for their outstanding ability in the performing or visual arts. The students are selected by their school to receive this honor. The banquet, with over 1,300 in attendance, is sponsored by Jostens, Horace Mann, the Department of Public Health, and the Connecticut National Guard. This year’s emcee was Tim Lammers of Fox 61 and the Keynote Speaker was Author and Columnist, Dr. Gina Barreca.

Class of 2019, Parents, and Guardians:

It’s time to order your senior’s cap and gown!
Orders can be placed online (link below) or by calling Jostens at 1-800-Jostens (567-8367)

The basic package is $25.00, which includes a cap, gown (your choice of red or black), and tassel.

Please note: The package for $37.00 includes an EXTRA tassel.

EO Smith HS – GRAD ORDERS – click here = https://www.jostens.com/apps/store/customer/1037252/E-O-Smith-High-School/ !
• Click “Graduation” box.
• Please scroll to bottom and click “Browse All Cap and Gown Products” this will lead you to the cap and gown only page.

If any additional graduation items are ordered (ex. Sweatshirt, t-shirts, etc.) they will be shipped directly to your home. The cap, gown, and tassel will be delivered to the school and distributed to your student prior to the commencement rehearsal.

THE ORDER DEADLINE IS FRIDAY, FEBRUARY 15TH.

ORDERS PLACED AFTER THIS DATE WILL INCUR A LATE FEE.

If you further assistance please contact jelliott@eosmith.org or 860-487-0877 x4960

post_text: The EO Smith Poetry Club has donated a large decorated wreath to the Wadsworth Atheneum’s annual fundraiser event “The Festival of Trees and Tradition”. The title of the wreath the students designed is “Words of Winter” and features ornaments decorated with stanzas from selected winter themed poems. It will be on public display until the final day of the event (December 9th).

2019 FFA Forestry CDE Champions

On November 30th 2018 these four E.O. Smith Students competed in the State Forestry Career Development Contest

Clay Farley 1st individual

Timothy Hill 3rd individual

post_text: Students from the Storrs FFA chapter, competed at the National FFA Convention in Indianapolis Indiana. The forestry team consisted of Brenna Lynn, Adam Luchon, Amelia Beauregard , and Vicki Janosi . This team placed Gold in the nation, 7th out of 41 states that competed from across the country. Individually Adam was 9th and Brenna 19th this placed them Gold in the nation, Amelia was silver and Vicki was awarded the bronze.

Please join us on Thursday, December 21st, 6:30-8:00 pm
in the E.O. Smith Atrium for the Winter Art Show.

In the case of inclement weather, the event will be postponed to January 4th.

The show will feature the work of art students from Drawing, Painting, Jewelry, Ceramics and Advanced Placement Art.

E.O. Smith Culinary and Music will provide catering and musical accompaniment.

T-shirts and other items will be available for sale. Proceeds will benefit E.O. Smith Art Club.

Smith has been recognized by the state for the way our school engaged students in the 2016 election and in civic education, specifically the cross-curricular work that engaged students in politics, the 54th House District Debate, the Mock Election, the Symposium and the collaboration with the Dodd Center to build a culture of democratic deliberation here at EO. A huge thank-you and congrats to our entire school (teachers, admin and students)!

post_text:
E.O Smith took first place honors in the Northeast Regional Science Bowl – South Division on March 4. E.O. has won this competition three years in a row and five times in the past ten years. This year’s team - John Zhou, Aham Lee, Chloe Gibson, Nico Martinez and Griffin Deans – answered 23 questions covering a variety of sciences such as biology, chemistry, physics, earth and space, math and energy. The team will advance to the National Finals to be held in Washington D.C. April 27-May 1.
An E.O. Smith team also took home second place in the new 3D Printing event at the Bowl. The E.O. team - Ilinca Johnson, Daniela Johnson, Matei Mandoiu – was tasked with designing, printing, adjusting and redesigning and printing turbine blades for maximum efficiency. E.O.'s blades were only 0.004 V/g off the winning mark.

Congratulations to E.O. Smith debaters Tim Watson and Kaylah Costa, who scored 82.5 and 81.5 points respectively, just a few points behind the winning score of 84.5 points, at the final debate tournament of the season. Both Kayla and Tim, along with David Liu, will represent E.O. Smith at the State tournament on March 18 at Amity High School.
E.O. Smith will also be hosting a special debate tournament – a qualifier for the Coolidge Cup Championship – on April 1st. Sophomores and Juniors interested in participating do not need to be active members of the debate team, but do need to contact Debate Team coach Kara Tamburri for more information. Students looking for volunteer hours can also earn 8+ by assisting at the event.

Last week the eight students from the Storrs FFA chapter, competed at the National FFA Convention in Indianapolis Indiana. The two teams comprised of Forestry and Natural Resources.

The forestry team consisted of Luc Poirier, Makenzie Hill, Valerie Freidmann, and Miranda Baldasty. This team placed Gold in the nation, 10th out of 40 states that competed. (this is the highest a CT Forestry team has ever placed on a national level) Individually Luc and Valerie placed Gold in the nation, Makenzie and Miranda place Silver.

The Natural Resources team consisted of Mitchell Sanchez, Zayne Allard, Sydney Pellerin, and Emanon Judkins. This team placed bronze in the nation, 33rd out of 42 states.

If you see any of these students please congratulate them on their countless hours they spent preparing for this contest.

(this is the highest a CT Forestry team has ever placed on a national level) Individually Luc and Valerie placed Gold in the nation, Makenzie and Miranda place Silver.

The Natural Resources team consisted of Mitchell Sanchez, Zayne Allard, Sydney Pellerin, and Emanon Judkins. This team placed bronze in the nation, 33rd out of 42 states.

If you see any of these students please congratulate them on their countless hours they spent preparing for this contest.

post_text: Save the date! We invite all to our 9th Annual "Midnight Madness" program on Friday, November 18th from 6pm-8pm in the gymnasium. The title of this event was “borrowed” from the college tradition of kicking off the basketball season at midnight by former students Ryan Olander and Lindsey Sundberg as part of their senior projects 9 years ago. The E.O. Smith version of this event is a student /faculty game against both the boys and girls varsity teams. This event is now co-sponsored by PNH and Panther Pride and has become a tradition at E.O. Smith. Hope to see you all there!

post_text:
Meet Samantha Wasilefsky, a new face to the E.O. Smith's faculty.

Samantha Wasilefsky teaches French language instruction at E.O. Smith. Samantha graduated from the University of Connecticut, with a Bachelor of Science in Education, and a Bachelor of Arts in French Cultural and Literary Studies, and is currently pursuing a Master of Arts in Curriculum and Instruction from University of Connecticut’s Neag School of Education.

Samantha grew up in Glastonbury, Connecticut and knew from a young age she wanted to be a teacher. She fell in love with the French language and culture when she participated in an exchange to France in high school.

post_text:
Meet Nathaniel Herter, a new face to the E.O. Smith's faculty.

Mr. Herter comes to E.O. Smith after serving as an instructional specialist at the University of Connecticut while obtaining his Master of Arts in Comparative Literary and Cultural Studies. He served as a general assistant in an advanced mythology course, and a graduate instructor in a two-semester elementary Latin course. He holds a Bachelor of Arts from the University of Connecticut in Classics and Ancient Mediterranean Studies.

Mr. Herter is proficient in Latin, Ancient Greek, and conversational in Irish (Gaeilge).

post_text:
Meet Amy Nocton, a new face to the E.O. Smith's faculty.

Amy Nocton is a Spanish and Italian educator with more than 20 years of teaching experience (23 years including private). She comes to E.O. Smith after teaching for eighteen years at RHAM High School. Ms. Nocton also instructed an English course for non-native English speakers at the University of Connecticut last year. She holds a master’s in Spanish from Middlebury College, a Master’s of Education from University of Hartford, and a Master’s in International Studies from the University of Connecticut.

Ms. Nocton has chaperoned students on many school trips, including destinations such as Costa Rica, Spain, Argentina/Uruguay, Quebec and Ecuador.

post_text:
Meet Kristopher Harlow, a new face to the E.O. Smith's faculty.

Mr. Harlow joins E.O. Smith after three years teaching social studies at High School of Commerce in Springfield, Massachusetts. He taught U.S. history and 20th Century World History, seeking to motivate and inspire students by exploring the relationship between academic social studies concepts and everyday life.

He successfully modified curriculum for English Language Learners and students with special needs. He holds a bachelor’s in history and secondary education from Westfield State University.

Mr. Harlow was a featured presenter at the 2014, High Schools That Work, National Conference in Nashville, TN, where he examined the importance and effectiveness of interdisciplinary teaming and professional learning communities.
